"""
calibration.py
==============
Post-hoc probability calibration for the hybrid fraud detection framework.

Paper
-----
"A Hybrid Deep Learning and Explainable AI Framework for Real-Time
Financial Fraud Detection in Dynamic Environments"

Why calibration matters for fraud detection
--------------------------------------------
The paper's cost-optimal decision rule (Lemma 1) is:

    predict fraud  iff  p_hat(x) >= tau*  where  tau* = c_FP / (c_FP + c_FN)

This rule is only optimal when p_hat(x) is a *calibrated* probability —
i.e. when P(y=1 | p_hat=0.7) ≈ 0.7 in reality.  An uncalibrated model
that systematically over- or under-estimates probabilities will shift the
effective decision boundary away from tau*, degrading recall or precision.

The paper quantifies this in Table 2:

    Dataset      Metric   Pre-calibration   Post-calibration
    -------------------------------------------------------
    Credit Card  ECE      6.1%              2.0%
    Credit Card  Brier    0.048             0.032
    IEEE-CIS     ECE      7.5%              2.5%
    PaySim       ECE      5.8%              1.9%

"The calibrated hybrid model was not only superior to the uncalibrated
variants, but also maintained constant precision with fixed recall across
folds with time."  (Results Discussion)

"A minor change in probability scores can radically change the
precision-recall trade-off when prevalence is low."  (Results Discussion)

Calibration methods provided
-----------------------------
1.  IsotonicCalibrator  — non-parametric isotonic regression (paper's
    primary method).  Fit on validation fold; applied at inference time.
2.  PlattCalibrator     — logistic (Platt) scaling, provided as a
    comparison baseline.
3.  TemperatureCalibrator — single scalar temperature T that divides
    logits before sigmoid; fast and interpretable.

All three implement a common CalibrationBase interface so they can be
swapped without changing downstream code.

Usage
-----
    from src.calibration import IsotonicCalibrator, CalibrationReport

    # Fit on validation fold raw scores
    cal = IsotonicCalibrator()
    cal.fit(raw_probs_val, y_val)

    # Apply to test scores
    calibrated_probs = cal.transform(raw_probs_test)

    # Measure improvement
    report = CalibrationReport.build(
        y_true=y_val,
        probs_before=raw_probs_val,
        probs_after=calibrated_probs,
        dataset_name="Credit Card",
    )
    print(report.summary())
    report.plot(save_path="results/figures/calibration_creditcard.png")
"""

